featured_reviews.review_id:
Built in 1472 by mahmood gawan in bidar.
An imposing three-storied building, the Madarasa was a renowned centre of learning with its own library, lecture halls, quarters for professors/ students and a mosque. The institution had scholars imparting knowledge of Arabic and Persian languages, theology, philosophy, mathematics, etc. The front of the building is adorned with tiles of various colours along with two stately minarets on each side. Extracts from the holy Quran have been engraved on some parts of the walls, the remains of which can be seen.

An imposing three-storied building, the Madarasa was a renowned centre of learning with its own library, lecture halls, quarters for professors/ students and a mosque. The institution had scholars imparting knowledge of Arabic and Persian languages, theology, philosophy, mathematics, etc. The front of the building is adorned with tiles of various colours along with two stately minarets on each side. Extracts from the holy Quran have been engraved on some parts of the walls, the remains of which can be seen.

featured_reviews.review_id:
This Madrasa was built in the year 1472 by Mahmud Gawan. It is an example of the regional style of Indo-Islamic architecture under the Bahmani Sultanate.
The building is one of those put by UNESCO on its "tentative list" to become a World Heritage Site in 2014, under the name Monuments and Forts of the Deccan Sultanate.
It describes an amazing piece of architecture by the Bahamani's .

featured_reviews.review_id:
A religious seminary dating back to the latter half of the 15th century, it was built by Mahmud Gawan a Persian scholar-in-exile who came to Bidar and set up the Madrasa.
He is believed to have set up the institution with his own money.
The structure is now more or less in ruins, though the mosque within still conducts daily prayers.
In 2014, UNESCO has earmarked this site for consideration as a World Heritage Site under "Monuments and Forts of the Deccan Sultanate", because it is 'an architectural gem'.
